VitB12 - DNAm MR power calculations

Thomas Battram

Background

Two EWAS were performed. One of maternal vitamin B12 levels and another of neonatal vitamin B12 levels, both measuring DNAm in cord blood. These EWAS identified 119 and 10 associations respectively (FDR < 0.05). To potentially improve causal inference for the associations, a Mendelian randomization analysis could be performed. This report looks to assess whether there is sufficient power to perform such analyses.

This report is split into four main sections:

  1. Data used and processing of data
  2. Power in a one-sample MR setting using maternal vitamin B12 as the exposure
  3. Power in a two-sample MR setting using neonatal vitamin B12 as the exposure
  4. Limitations of these power analyses

For sections 2 and 3, the power to detect an association in an MR context at the same magnitude as the observational associations is assessed.

Data

For both studies GWAS of vitamin B12 from Grarup N et al.(N = 45,576) were used to identify suitable instruments. The study identified 11 genetic variants associated at 5x10-8 with vitamin B12 levels in a European population. To prevent double counting instruments and so artificially increasing precision, genetic variants in linkage disequilibrium (r2 > 0.001) were identified and the one with the weakest association was removed. No variants were in linkage disequilibrium so all were kept. A summary of the SNPs can be found in Table 1.

The combined variance explained (r2) of of the 11 SNPs was 0.045 and the F-statistic for an instrument that combined all 11 SNPs (e.g.a GRS) was 196.

For the two-sample MR, the first sample was assumed to be the vitamin B12 GWAS and the second sample was assumed to be GoDMC (N = roughly 25,000).

The TwoSampleMR package was used to help format some data and clump the exposure SNPs. All code for the analyses can be found here: https://github.com/thomasbattram/vitb12-mr-power-calculations

One-sample MR

Code was taken from the one-sample MR power calculator shiny application (https://shiny.cnsgenomics.com/mRnd/), which is based on the Brion et al.2013 publication. It was assumed that the instrument being used for the MR would be a genetic-risk score (GRS) for vitamin B12 formed from the 11 variants shown in Table 1.

The 119 CpG sites used for the one-sample MR power calculations were those that were identified in the EWAS of maternal vitamin B12 at FDR < 5%.

Results

At a sample size of 3000, the median power to detect the observational association using 1SMR was 0.15. The greatest power was to detect an association between vitamin B12 and DNA methylation at cg16991589 (power = 0.49). The range of powers for each CpG site across sample sizes ranging from 1000 to 3000 are presented in Figure 1. Full results can be seen in Table 2.

Figure 1: Range of powers in 1SMR. The violin plot shows the range of powers to detect associations at least as large as the observational association across sample sizes for each DNA methylation site.

Figure 2: Sample size required for 80% power in a one-sample MR setting

Two-sample MR

The same SNPs were used for the power calculation in the two-sample MR. The sample size was set to be 25000, which is roughly the sample size of the GoDMC consortium, but may vary depending on the CpG site.

The 10 CpG sites used for the power calculations were those that were identified in the EWAS of neonatal vitamin B12 at FDR < 5%.

Results

Power to detect associations was very low (<5%). Results are presented in Table 3.

Table 3: Full power results for 2SMR

Limitations

One-sample MR

  • The variance of DNAm was unknown. If the variance of DNAm in ARIES is not representative of the other cohorts in the meta-analysis then the power estimates will vary.
  • The confounded (or unadjusted) effect estimates were set to be the effect estimates from the EWAS. It is likely the confounded estimates are further from the null (assuming the EWAS estimates provided were adjusted for confounders). If this is the case then there will be greater power in the 1SMR than reported here. However, unless the confounded estimates are greatly different to the adjusted effect estimates then the power increase will be minimal - e.g.if the estimates are 50% greater then the increase in power is roughly 1% for each CpG site.
